if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_ext_nose']=[
  {q:"Little's area, repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT, is located on the:",o:["Roof of nasal cavity","Anterior nasal septum","Inferior turbinate","Posterior choana"],a:1,e:"Anterior nasal septum fits the location of Little's area; characteristic vascular plexus responsible for common anterior epistaxis. Bleeding occurs clinically after trauma or dryness frequently.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Kiesselbach plexus forms through anastomosis of septal branches from facial, maxillary, and ophthalmic arteries symptomatically.<br><br>Roof of nasal cavity (option A) contains olfactory mucosa; inferior turbinate (option C) conditions airflow; posterior choana (option D) communicates nasopharynx. Therefore Little area lies over anterior septum clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve supply of nasal vestibule is mainly derived from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Optic nerve","Infraorbital nerve"],a:3,e:"Infraorbital nerve supply fits nasal vestibule sensory innervation; characteristic branch of maxillary division of trigeminal nerve. Vestibular pain becomes clinically localized anteriorly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: vestibular skin receives sensory fibers from infraorbital and external nasal nerve branches symptomatically.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) supplies muscles; optic nerve (option C) mediates vision; glossopharyngeal nerve (option B) innervates pharynx. Therefore infraorbital nerve contributes major vestibular sensation clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The physiological function of inferior turbinate is primarily:",o:["Olfaction only","Speech production","Taste sensation","Humidification and warming of inspired air"],a:3,e:"Humidification and warming of inspired air fit inferior turbinate physiology; characteristic nasal air conditioning function. Rich vascularity contributes clinically efficient airflow conditioning.<br><br>Standard physiology: turbinate mucosa increases surface area causing filtration, humidification, and temperature regulation symptomatically.<br><br>Olfaction only (option A) mainly involves roof mucosa; taste sensation (option C) depends gustatory pathways; speech production (option B) involves laryngeal mechanisms. Therefore inferior turbinate primarily conditions inspired air clinically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The upper lateral cartilage of nose is attached superiorly to the:",o:["Nasal bone","Septal cartilage","Inferior turbinate","Maxillary sinus"],a:0,e:"Nasal bone attachment fits superior relation of upper lateral cartilage; characteristic external nasal framework anatomy. Structural support maintains clinically nasal contour and airway patency.<br><br>Standard anatomy: upper lateral cartilages articulate medially with septal cartilage and superiorly beneath nasal bones symptomatically.<br><br>Septal cartilage (option B) forms medial support only; inferior turbinate (option C) lies intranasally; maxillary sinus (option D) remains unrelated externally. Therefore upper lateral cartilage attaches superiorly to nasal bone clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The blood supply of Little's area includes branches from all except:",o:["Facial artery","Maxillary artery","Ophthalmic artery","Vertebral artery"],a:3,e:"Vertebral artery exclusion fits blood supply of Little's area; characteristic septal vascular plexus anatomy. Anterior epistaxis develops clinically from fragile septal vessels.<br><br>Standard anatomy: septal branches arise from facial, maxillary, and ophthalmic arterial systems forming Kiesselbach plexus symptomatically.<br><br>Facial artery (option A), maxillary artery (option B), and ophthalmic artery (option C) contribute directly. Therefore vertebral artery lacks participation in Little area circulation clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The olfactory mucosa is located mainly over the:",o:["Inferior turbinate","Roof of nasal cavity","Nasal vestibule","Nasal floor"],a:1,e:"Roof of nasal cavity fits olfactory mucosa location; characteristic sensory epithelium for smell perception. Olfactory receptor neurons function clinically within superior nasal regions.<br><br>Standard anatomy: olfactory epithelium covers superior septum and superior turbinate areas symptomatically.<br><br>Inferior turbinate (option A) mainly conditions air; nasal vestibule (option C) contains skin; nasal floor (option D) conducts airflow inferiorly. Therefore olfactory mucosa occupies nasal roof clinically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A furuncle of nasal vestibule is dangerous because venous drainage communicates with the:",o:["Internal jugular vein only","Vertebral plexus","Pulmonary veins","Cavernous sinus"],a:3,e:"Cavernous sinus communication fits danger of vestibular furuncle; characteristic facial venous drainage pathway. Infection may spread clinically producing cavernous sinus thrombosis.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial veins communicate with angular and ophthalmic venous systems lacking valves symptomatically.<br><br>Internal jugular vein only (option A) oversimplifies drainage; pulmonary veins (option C) lack relevance; vertebral plexus (option B) remains unrelated. Therefore vestibular infections may spread toward cavernous sinus clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The cartilaginous part forms approximately what proportion of external nose?",o:["Upper one third","Lower one third","Lower two thirds","Entire nose"],a:2,e:"Lower two thirds formation fits cartilaginous contribution to external nose; characteristic nasal skeletal anatomy. Flexibility remains clinically greater within inferior nasal portions.<br><br>Standard anatomy: nasal bones form upper third whereas septal, upper lateral, and alar cartilages form lower regions symptomatically.<br><br>Upper one third (option A) represents bony framework; lower one third (option B) underestimates cartilage extent; entire nose (option D) ignores bony component. Therefore cartilage forms lower two thirds clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Which muscle is primarily responsible for dilating the nostril during deep inspiration?",o:["Levator labii superioris","Nasalis muscle","Buccinator","Orbicularis oris"],a:1,e:"Nasalis muscle fits primary nostril dilator during deep inspiration; characteristic external nasal muscle function. Nostril widening improves clinically airflow resistance reduction.<br><br>Standard anatomy: alar fibers of nasalis elevate and flare nostrils during forceful breathing symptomatically.<br><br>Levator labii superioris (option A) elevates upper lip; buccinator (option C) compresses cheek; orbicularis oris (option D) closes mouth. Therefore nasalis muscle dilates nostrils clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory nerve supply of anterior nasal septum is mainly through the:",o:["Anterior ethmoidal nerve","Vagus nerve","Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:0,e:"Anterior ethmoidal nerve supply fits sensory innervation of anterior nasal septum; characteristic ophthalmic trigeminal branch distribution. Septal pain localizes clinically anteriorly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: anterior ethmoidal nerve enters nasal cavity through anterior ethmoidal foramen supplying septal mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option B) supplies larynx; facial nerve (option C) innervates facial muscles; hypoglossal nerve (option D) controls tongue movement. Therefore anterior septal sensation mainly arises from anterior ethmoidal nerve clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common nasal deformity repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT is:",o:["Saddle nose deformity","Crooked columella","Bifid nose","Deviated nose"],a:3,e:"Deviated nose fits the commonest nasal deformity recalled in examinations; characteristic traumatic or developmental external nasal deviation. Nasal obstruction develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: septal deviation and asymmetric cartilaginous displacement alter external nasal alignment symptomatically.<br><br>Saddle nose deformity (option A) follows cartilage destruction; bifid nose (option C) remains congenital; crooked columella (option B) occurs less frequently. Therefore deviated nose represents commonest nasal deformity clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Saddle nose deformity classically results from destruction of the:",o:["Upper lateral cartilage","Frontal sinus","Inferior turbinate","Septal cartilage"],a:3,e:"Septal cartilage destruction fits saddle nose deformity; characteristic collapse of nasal dorsum support. External nose appears clinically depressed centrally.<br><br>Standard pathology: trauma, syphilis, granulomatous disease, or septal abscess may destroy septal cartilage symptomatically.<br><br>Upper lateral cartilage (option A) contributes sidewall support only; inferior turbinate (option C) lies intranasally; frontal sinus (option B) remains unrelated externally. Therefore saddle nose follows septal cartilage loss clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with unilateral choanal atresia most commonly presents with:",o:["Severe neonatal cyanosis","Persistent unilateral nasal discharge","Facial palsy","Epistaxis only"],a:1,e:"Persistent unilateral nasal discharge fits unilateral choanal atresia presentation; characteristic congenital posterior nasal obstruction. Symptoms become clinically less severe than bilateral disease.<br><br>Standard pathology: posterior nasal aperture remains blocked by bony or membranous tissue symptomatically.<br><br>Severe neonatal cyanosis (option A) characterizes bilateral atresia; facial palsy (option C) lacks association; isolated epistaxis (option D) remains uncommon. Therefore unilateral choanal atresia presents with persistent unilateral discharge clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral choanal atresia in neonates classically presents with:",o:["Cyclical cyanosis relieved by crying","Hearing loss","Vertigo","Trismus"],a:0,e:"Cyclical cyanosis relieved by crying fits bilateral choanal atresia in neonates; characteristic obligate nasal breathing problem. Respiratory distress develops clinically immediately after birth.<br><br>Standard physiology: crying permits oral airflow temporarily relieving cyanosis caused by bilateral posterior nasal obstruction symptomatically.<br><br>Hearing loss (option B), vertigo (option C), and trismus (option D) lack direct association. Therefore cyclical neonatal cyanosis strongly suggests bilateral choanal atresia clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Rhinophyma most commonly affects the:",o:["Nasal dorsum","Nasal floor","Columella","Nasal tip"],a:3,e:"Nasal tip involvement fits rhinophyma; characteristic bulbous enlargement caused by sebaceous gland hypertrophy. Elderly men develop clinically nodular deformity frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic rosacea produces fibrosis, vascular enlargement, and sebaceous hyperplasia symptomatically.<br><br>Nasal dorsum (option A) forms upper external nose; columella (option C) separates nostrils; nasal floor (option B) remains internal. Therefore rhinophyma predominantly affects nasal tip clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A septal hematoma left untreated may lead to:",o:["Saddle nose deformity","Meningitis only","Glaucoma","Facial paralysis"],a:0,e:"Saddle nose deformity fits untreated septal hematoma complications; characteristic septal cartilage necrosis outcome. Nasal bridge collapse develops clinically subsequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: hematoma separates cartilage from perichondrial blood supply causing ischemic necrosis symptomatically.<br><br>Meningitis only (option B) remains less common; glaucoma (option C) lacks relation; facial paralysis (option D) involves seventh nerve dysfunction. Therefore untreated septal hematoma causes saddle nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of deviated nasal septum in recalls is:",o:["Congenital syphilis","Trauma","Tuberculosis","Rhinoscleroma"],a:1,e:"Trauma fits the commonest cause of deviated nasal septum in recalls; characteristic external nasal injury complication. Nasal obstruction develops clinically frequently afterward.<br><br>Standard pathology: forceful displacement of septal cartilage and bone alters normal midline alignment symptomatically.<br><br>Congenital syphilis (option A) causes saddle nose; tuberculosis (option C) rarely affects septum; rhinoscleroma (option D) causes granulomatous disease. Therefore trauma commonly produces septal deviation clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with broad nasal bridge, telecanthus, and anosmia most likely has:",o:["Kallmann syndrome","Bell palsy","Meniere disease","Otosclerosis"],a:0,e:"Kallmann syndrome fits anosmia with craniofacial developmental abnormalities; characteristic olfactory pathway developmental defect. Delayed puberty develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: failed migration of gonadotropin releasing hormone neurons associates with olfactory bulb abnormalities symptomatically.<br><br>Bell palsy (option B) affects facial nerve; Meniere disease (option C) causes vertigo; otosclerosis (option D) causes conductive hearing loss. Therefore anosmia with facial anomalies suggests Kallmann syndrome clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The external nasal deformity produced by depressed nasal bridge is termed:",o:["Crooked nose","Saddle nose","Hump nose","Pinched nose"],a:1,e:"Saddle nose fits depressed nasal bridge deformity; characteristic collapse of septal support. External nasal dorsum appears clinically sunken centrally.<br><br>Standard pathology: cartilage destruction follows trauma, infection, septal hematoma, or granulomatous disease symptomatically.<br><br>Crooked nose (option A) indicates lateral deviation; hump nose (option C) shows dorsal prominence; pinched nose (option D) narrows nasal valve. Therefore depressed bridge deformity represents saddle nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with nasal trauma develops bilateral soft fluctuant septal swelling causing obstruction. The diagnosis is:",o:["Septal hematoma","Antrochoanal polyp","Nasal glioma","Rhinophyma"],a:0,e:"Septal hematoma fits bilateral soft fluctuant septal swelling after nasal trauma; characteristic emergency nasal condition. Nasal obstruction develops clinically rapidly following injury.<br><br>Standard pathology: blood accumulates between septal cartilage and perichondrium threatening cartilage viability symptomatically.<br><br>Antrochoanal polyp (option B) arises from maxillary sinus; nasal glioma (option C) remains congenital; rhinophyma (option D) affects nasal tip skin. Therefore traumatic bilateral septal swelling indicates septal hematoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common bone fractured in facial trauma repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT is the:",o:["Frontal bone","Maxilla","Zygomatic bone","Nasal bone"],a:3,e:"Nasal bone fracture fits the commonest facial skeletal injury; characteristic prominence and central facial location predispose trauma clinically. Epistaxis and deformity commonly develop afterward.<br><br>Standard anatomy: thin paired nasal bones project anteriorly and articulate with frontal and maxillary bones symptomatically during impact injuries.<br><br>Frontal bone (option A) fractures require severe trauma; zygomatic bone (option C) fractures affect cheek prominence; maxilla (option B) fractures involve midface. Therefore nasal bone fractures occur most frequently clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops bilateral nasal obstruction after trauma with soft septal swelling. The diagnosis is:",o:["Septal hematoma","Antrochoanal polyp","Rhinophyma","Choanal atresia"],a:0,e:"Septal hematoma fits bilateral obstructive septal swelling following nasal trauma; characteristic blood collection beneath septal perichondrium. Prompt drainage becomes clinically essential.<br><br>Standard pathology: hematoma separates cartilage from nutritional blood supply causing ischemic necrosis symptomatically.<br><br>Antrochoanal polyp (option B) originates from maxillary sinus; rhinophyma (option C) affects nasal tip skin; choanal atresia (option D) remains congenital. Therefore traumatic septal swelling suggests septal hematoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important complication of untreated septal hematoma is:",o:["Meningitis","Facial palsy","Hearing loss","Saddle nose deformity"],a:3,e:"Saddle nose deformity fits major complication of untreated septal hematoma; characteristic septal cartilage necrosis outcome. Nasal bridge collapse appears clinically later.<br><br>Standard pathology: interrupted perichondrial blood supply produces ischemic destruction of septal cartilage symptomatically.<br><br>Meningitis (option A) occurs rarely; hearing loss (option C) lacks association; facial palsy (option B) involves seventh nerve dysfunction. Therefore untreated septal hematoma commonly causes saddle nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"CSF rhinorrhea after nasal trauma most commonly results from fracture involving the:",o:["Nasal septum","Cribriform plate","Inferior turbinate","Maxillary sinus"],a:1,e:"Cribriform plate fracture fits cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea after nasal trauma; characteristic anterior cranial fossa injury. Clear watery discharge appears clinically from nose.<br><br>Standard anatomy: olfactory nerve fibers traverse cribriform plate creating communication between cranial cavity and nasal cavity symptomatically after fractures.<br><br>Nasal septum (option A) separates cavities; inferior turbinate (option C) conditions airflow; maxillary sinus (option D) lies laterally. Therefore traumatic CSF rhinorrhea commonly follows cribriform plate fractures clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recent nasal trauma develops telecanthus and CSF rhinorrhea. The most likely fracture is:",o:["Le Fort I fracture","Zygomatic fracture","Mandibular fracture","Nasoethmoidal fracture"],a:3,e:"Nasoethmoidal fracture fits telecanthus with cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea after trauma; characteristic central midface injury pattern. Medial canthal displacement develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard anatomy: fractures involve ethmoid labyrinth and medial orbital structures adjacent to anterior cranial base symptomatically.<br><br>Le Fort I fracture (option A) affects lower maxilla; mandibular fracture (option C) involves jaw; zygomatic fracture (option B) affects cheek prominence. Therefore telecanthus with CSF leak suggests nasoethmoidal injury clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred timing for reduction of uncomplicated nasal bone fracture in adults is usually within:",o:["Twenty four hours only","Seven to ten days","One month","Six months"],a:1,e:"Seven to ten days fits preferred reduction timing for uncomplicated adult nasal fractures; characteristic period after edema subsides clinically. Bone alignment remains correctable before fixation occurs.<br><br>Standard management: delayed manipulation beyond two weeks increases difficulty because fracture fragments consolidate symptomatically.<br><br>Twenty four hours only (option A) may precede edema resolution; one month (option C) and six months (option D) represent excessively delayed intervention. Therefore reduction commonly occurs within seven to ten days clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom immediately following nasal fracture is:",o:["Hearing loss","Dysphagia","Vertigo","Epistaxis"],a:3,e:"Epistaxis fits the commonest immediate symptom following nasal fracture; characteristic vascular mucosal injury manifestation. Nasal swelling and deformity develop clinically simultaneously.<br><br>Standard pathology: trauma disrupts septal and mucosal vessels producing anterior nasal bleeding symptomatically.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A) involves auditory pathways; vertigo (option C) suggests vestibular dysfunction; dysphagia (option B) relates pharyngeal pathology. Therefore epistaxis commonly follows nasal fracture clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral watery nasal discharge increasing on bending forward after trauma most likely has:",o:["Allergic rhinitis","Rhinophyma","Vasomotor rhinitis","CSF rhinorrhea"],a:3,e:"CSF rhinorrhea fits unilateral watery nasal discharge worsening on bending forward after trauma; characteristic anterior skull base leak. Risk of meningitis increases clinically significantly.<br><br>Standard pathology: fracture of cribriform region permits cerebrospinal fluid leakage into nasal cavity symptomatically.<br><br>Allergic rhinitis (option A) causes bilateral watery discharge; vasomotor rhinitis (option C) lacks trauma association; rhinophyma (option B) affects nasal tip skin. Therefore post traumatic watery rhinorrhea suggests CSF leakage clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important step in examination of nasal trauma is exclusion of:",o:["Septal hematoma","Rhinitis medicamentosa","Atrophic rhinitis","Nasal polyp"],a:0,e:"Septal hematoma exclusion fits essential examination after nasal trauma; characteristic emergency requiring urgent drainage. Cartilage necrosis develops clinically if diagnosis becomes delayed.<br><br>Standard pathology: hematoma compromises septal blood supply causing ischemic destruction symptomatically.<br><br>Rhinitis medicamentosa (option B) results from decongestant overuse; atrophic rhinitis (option C) causes crusting; nasal polyp (option D) develops chronically. Therefore septal hematoma must always be excluded clinically after trauma.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which deformity most commonly follows improperly treated nasal fracture?",o:["Saddle nose","Deviated nose","Rhinophyma","Choanal atresia"],a:1,e:"Deviated nose fits common sequela of improperly treated nasal fracture; characteristic asymmetric healing deformity. Persistent nasal obstruction develops clinically frequently afterward.<br><br>Standard pathology: displaced nasal bones and septal structures heal in abnormal alignment symptomatically.<br><br>Saddle nose (option A) follows cartilage loss; rhinophyma (option C) results from rosacea; choanal atresia (option D) remains congenital. Therefore malunited fractures commonly produce deviated nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful boil in the nasal vestibule is termed:",o:["Furunculosis","Rhinoscleroma","Rhinophyma","Choanal atresia"],a:0,e:"Furunculosis fits painful boil formation within nasal vestibule; characteristic staphylococcal infection of hair follicles. Tender swelling develops clinically near nostril margin.<br><br>Standard pathology: vestibular skin containing vibrissae becomes infected producing localized abscess formation symptomatically.<br><br>Rhinoscleroma (option B) causes granulomatous disease; rhinophyma (option C) enlarges nasal tip; choanal atresia (option D) remains congenital obstruction. Therefore vestibular boils represent furunculosis clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest organism causing nasal vestibulitis is:",o:["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus","Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis","Streptococcus pneumoniae"],a:1,e:"Staphylococcus aureus fits commonest organism causing nasal vestibulitis; characteristic infection of vestibular hair follicles. Pain and crusting develop clinically anteriorly.<br><br>Standard pathology: minor trauma and nose picking predispose bacterial invasion of vestibular skin symptomatically.<br><br>Pseudomonas aeruginosa (option A) commonly infects external ear; Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis (option C) causes rhinoscleroma; Streptococcus pneumoniae (option D) frequently causes sinusitis. Therefore staphylococcal infection predominates clinically in vestibulitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Furunculosis of nasal vestibule is considered dangerous because infection may spread to the:",o:["Cavernous sinus","Middle ear","Trachea","Thyroid gland"],a:0,e:"Cavernous sinus spread fits danger of nasal vestibular furunculosis; characteristic facial venous communication without valves. Intracranial complications develop clinically rarely but seriously.<br><br>Standard anatomy: facial and angular veins communicate directly with ophthalmic veins draining toward cavernous sinus symptomatically.<br><br>Middle ear (option B), trachea (option C), and thyroid gland (option D) lack direct venous communication. Therefore vestibular infections may spread toward cavernous sinus clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Rhinoscleroma is caused by:",o:["Staphylococcus aureus","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis"],a:3,e:"Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis fits causative organism of rhinoscleroma; characteristic chronic granulomatous nasal infection. Nasal obstruction develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: granulomatous inflammation produces nodular thickening and fibrosis of upper respiratory mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (option A) causes vestibulitis; Corynebacterium diphtheriae (option C) causes diphtheria; Mycobacterium tuberculosis (option B) produces tuberculous lesions. Therefore rhinoscleroma results from Klebsiella infection clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The characteristic cells seen in rhinoscleroma are:",o:["Reed Sternberg cells","Mikulicz cells","Langhans giant cells","Plasma blasts"],a:1,e:"Mikulicz cells fit histopathology of rhinoscleroma; characteristic foamy macrophages containing causative bacilli. Granulomatous inflammation progresses clinically slowly.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic infection stimulates plasma cell infiltration and fibrosis within respiratory mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Reed Sternberg cells (option A) occur in Hodgkin lymphoma; Langhans giant cells (option C) appear in tuberculosis; plasma blasts (option D) lack diagnostic specificity. Therefore Mikulicz cells characterize rhinoscleroma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with crusting, foul smell, and widened nasal cavity most likely has:",o:["Furunculosis","Septal hematoma","Vestibular papilloma","Atrophic rhinitis"],a:3,e:"Atrophic rhinitis fits crusting with foul smell and widened nasal cavities; characteristic mucosal atrophy disorder. Patients may remain clinically unaware of offensive odor.<br><br>Standard pathology: mucosal and turbinate atrophy produce crust formation with secondary bacterial colonization symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) causes painful vestibular boil; vestibular papilloma (option C) produces wart like lesions; septal hematoma (option B) follows trauma. Therefore foul crusting suggests atrophic rhinitis clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest predisposing factor for nasal vestibulitis is:",o:["Nose picking","Swimming","High altitude","Smoking only"],a:0,e:"Nose picking fits commonest predisposing factor for vestibulitis; characteristic traumatic inoculation of vestibular hair follicles. Painful crusting develops clinically anteriorly.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated local trauma permits staphylococcal bacterial invasion of vestibular skin symptomatically.<br><br>Swimming (option B) predisposes otitis externa; high altitude (option C) causes pressure symptoms; smoking only (option D) lacks primary association. Therefore nose picking commonly precedes vestibulitis clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Rhinoscleroma most commonly involves the:",o:["Larynx only","Oral tongue","Middle ear","Nose"],a:3,e:"Nasal involvement fits rhinoscleroma most commonly; characteristic chronic granulomatous disease of upper respiratory tract. Progressive obstruction develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: granulomatous infiltration and fibrosis primarily affect nasal mucosa symptomatically before spreading elsewhere.<br><br>Larynx only (option A) underestimates nasal predominance; middle ear (option C) lacks classic association; oral tongue (option B) remains uncommon. Therefore rhinoscleroma commonly begins within nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of furunculosis of nasal vestibule primarily includes:",o:["Broad spectrum antibiotics","Immediate septoplasty","Mastoidectomy","Tympanoplasty"],a:0,e:"Broad spectrum antibiotics fit treatment of nasal vestibular furunculosis; characteristic staphylococcal skin infection management. Manipulation should be clinically avoided because of venous spread risk.<br><br>Standard treatment: systemic antibiotics with local hygiene reduce infection and prevent cavernous sinus complications symptomatically.<br><br>Immediate septoplasty (option B) corrects septal deviation; mastoidectomy (option C) treats mastoid disease; tympanoplasty (option D) repairs tympanic membrane. Therefore antibiotics remain primary therapy clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A chronic granulomatous disease causing woody induration of nasal tissues in endemic regions is:",o:["Furunculosis","Rhinoscleroma","Septal hematoma","Rhinophyma"],a:1,e:"Rhinoscleroma fits chronic granulomatous disease causing woody nasal induration; characteristic endemic upper airway infection. Progressive fibrosis develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis infection stimulates granulomatous inflammation and scar formation symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) causes acute boils; septal hematoma (option C) follows trauma; rhinophyma (option D) enlarges nasal tip. Therefore woody granulomatous nasal disease indicates rhinoscleroma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of external nose repeatedly recalled in FCPS and JCAT is:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Osteoma","Neuroblastoma"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma fits the commonest malignant tumor of external nose; characteristic slow growing sun related cutaneous malignancy. Lesions occur clinically frequently over nasal dorsum.<br><br>Standard pathology: prolonged ultraviolet exposure induces malignant transformation of basal epidermal cells symptomatically.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option B) usually arises sinonasally; osteoma (option C) remains benign bony tumor; neuroblastoma (option D) lacks common nasal skin association. Therefore basal cell carcinoma predominates clinically over external nose.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A pearly nodular lesion with rolled edges over the nose is most suggestive of:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Papilloma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma fits pearly nodular lesion with rolled margins over the nose; characteristic appearance of rodent ulcer. Slow enlargement occurs clinically over years.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant basal epidermal cells invade locally with minimal metastatic potential symptomatically.<br><br>Squamous cell carcinoma (option A) ulcerates aggressively; melanoma (option C) appears pigmented; papilloma (option D) remains benign epithelial growth. Therefore pearly rolled lesions strongly suggest basal cell carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important etiological factor for carcinoma of external nose is:",o:["Smoking","Nasal trauma","Swimming","Chronic sun exposure"],a:3,e:"Chronic sun exposure fits major etiological factor for carcinoma of external nose; characteristic ultraviolet induced skin malignancy mechanism. Fair skinned individuals develop clinically higher risk.<br><br>Standard pathology: cumulative ultraviolet radiation damages epidermal cellular DNA producing malignant transformation symptomatically.<br><br>Smoking (option A) strongly associates oral cancers; swimming (option C) lacks carcinogenic role; nasal trauma (option B) does not directly cause malignancy. Therefore ultraviolet exposure commonly causes external nasal carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"Squamous cell carcinoma of nasal vestibule most commonly presents with:",o:["Painless ulcerative lesion","Sudden blindness","Hearing loss","Vertigo"],a:0,e:"Painless ulcerative lesion fits squamous cell carcinoma of nasal vestibule; characteristic malignant epithelial growth pattern. Progressive crusting and bleeding occur clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant squamous epithelium invades surrounding vestibular tissues causing ulceration symptomatically.<br><br>Sudden blindness (option B), hearing loss (option C), and vertigo (option D) lack direct vestibular tumor association. Therefore painless ulcerative lesions suggest vestibular carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The tumor classically called \"rodent ulcer\" is:",o:["Melanoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Fibroma","Hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma fits the term rodent ulcer; characteristic locally invasive ulcerative nasal skin malignancy. Slow tissue destruction develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant basal epidermal cells infiltrate surrounding tissues while metastasis remains uncommon symptomatically.<br><br>Melanoma (option A) presents pigmented lesions; fibroma (option C) remains benign connective tissue tumor; hemangioma (option D) arises from blood vessels. Therefore rodent ulcer refers to basal cell carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which malignant tumor of nose has highest metastatic potential?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Papilloma","Rhinophyma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits malignant nasal tumor with highest metastatic potential; characteristic aggressive epithelial malignancy behavior. Regional lymph node spread develops clinically more frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant squamous cells invade deeply and metastasize through lymphatic channels symptomatically.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (option A) metastasizes rarely; papilloma (option C) remains benign; rhinophyma (option D) represents sebaceous hypertrophy. Therefore squamous carcinoma shows greater metastatic tendency clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A black pigmented irregular lesion over external nose should raise suspicion of:",o:["Papilloma","Sebaceous cyst","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma"],a:3,e:"Melanoma fits irregular black pigmented lesion over external nose; characteristic malignant melanocytic neoplasm. Rapid progression and metastasis occur clinically aggressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: atypical melanocytes proliferate uncontrollably with early invasive and metastatic potential symptomatically.<br><br>Papilloma (option A) forms wart like growths; basal cell carcinoma (option C) appears pearly; sebaceous cyst (option B) remains benign. Therefore irregular pigmented lesions suggest melanoma clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred treatment for localized basal cell carcinoma of external nose is:",o:["Radiotherapy alone","Observation only","Chemotherapy only","Wide local excision"],a:3,e:"Wide local excision fits treatment of localized basal cell carcinoma over external nose; characteristic curative surgical management. Local recurrence decreases clinically with adequate margins.<br><br>Standard treatment: complete tumor removal preserves surrounding healthy tissue and prevents progressive local invasion symptomatically.<br><br>Radiotherapy alone (option A) serves selected patients; chemotherapy only (option C) lacks primary role; observation only (option B) risks progression. Therefore surgical excision remains preferred clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A wart like benign epithelial tumor arising in nasal vestibule is termed:",o:["Papilloma","Chondroma","Sarcoma","Fibrosarcoma"],a:0,e:"Papilloma fits wart like benign epithelial tumor of nasal vestibule; characteristic exophytic epithelial proliferation. Obstruction or irritation develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: benign squamous epithelial overgrowth produces papillary projections symptomatically.<br><br>Chondroma (option B) arises from cartilage; sarcoma (option C) and fibrosarcoma (option D) represent malignant mesenchymal tumors. Therefore wart like vestibular growths indicate papilloma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site for basal cell carcinoma on external nose is the:",o:["Ala nasi","Nasal dorsum","Columella","Nasal floor"],a:1,e:"Nasal dorsum fits commonest site for basal cell carcinoma over external nose; characteristic chronically sun exposed region. Slow growing lesions develop clinically frequently there.<br><br>Standard pathology: prolonged ultraviolet exposure damages basal epidermal cells over prominent nasal surfaces symptomatically.<br><br>Ala nasi (option A) may also become involved; columella (option C) receives less exposure; nasal floor (option D) remains internal. Therefore basal cell carcinoma commonly affects nasal dorsum clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with recurrent anterior epistaxis from Little's area. The artery contributing least to this plexus is:",o:["Sphenopalatine artery","Greater palatine artery","Vertebral artery","Superior labial artery"],a:2,e:"Vertebral artery exclusion fits vascular anatomy of Little area; characteristic anterior septal anastomotic plexus causing recurrent epistaxis. Bleeding occurs clinically after trauma or mucosal dryness.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Kiesselbach plexus receives septal branches from facial, maxillary, and ophthalmic arterial systems symptomatically.<br><br>Sphenopalatine artery (option A), greater palatine artery (option B), and superior labial artery (option D) contribute directly. Therefore vertebral artery lacks involvement within Little area circulation clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate develops cyanosis during feeding which improves while crying. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Nasal vestibulitis","Rhinophyma","Deviated nasal septum","Bilateral choanal atresia"],a:3,e:"Bilateral choanal atresia fits neonatal cyanosis relieved by crying; characteristic posterior nasal obstruction in obligate nasal breathers. Respiratory distress develops clinically immediately after birth.<br><br>Standard physiology: crying permits temporary oral airflow bypassing blocked posterior choanae symptomatically.<br><br>Nasal vestibulitis (option A) causes localized infection; deviated nasal septum (option C) rarely causes neonatal obstruction; rhinophyma (option B) affects elderly adults. Therefore cyclical neonatal cyanosis indicates bilateral choanal atresia clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of furunculosis of nasal vestibule is:",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Septal perforation","Conductive deafness","Bell palsy"],a:0,e:"Cavernous sinus thrombosis fits dangerous complication of vestibular furunculosis; characteristic venous spread from facial danger area. Intracranial sepsis develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: valveless facial and ophthalmic veins communicate directly with cavernous sinus symptomatically permitting retrograde infection spread.<br><br>Septal perforation (option B) follows septal disease; conductive deafness (option C) involves middle ear pathology; Bell palsy (option D) affects facial nerve. Therefore vestibular furunculosis risks cavernous sinus thrombosis clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with trauma develops depressed nasal bridge due to septal cartilage destruction. The deformity is called:",o:["Crooked nose","Hump nose","Saddle nose","Pinched nose"],a:2,e:"Saddle nose fits depressed nasal bridge after septal cartilage destruction; characteristic collapse deformity of nasal dorsum. Nasal obstruction develops clinically frequently afterward.<br><br>Standard pathology: septal hematoma, trauma, infection, or granulomatous disease may destroy cartilaginous support symptomatically.<br><br>Crooked nose (option A) indicates deviation; hump nose (option B) shows dorsal prominence; pinched nose (option D) narrows nasal valve. Therefore depressed bridge deformity represents saddle nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory innervation of nasal vestibule is mainly through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Infraorbital nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:1,e:"Infraorbital nerve supply fits sensory innervation of nasal vestibule; characteristic branch distribution from maxillary trigeminal division. Vestibular pain localizes clinically anteriorly.<br><br>Standard anatomy: vestibular skin and surrounding tissues receive sensory fibers through infraorbital and external nasal nerves symptomatically.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) supplies facial muscles; glossopharyngeal nerve (option C) innervates pharynx; vagus nerve (option D) supplies larynx. Therefore infraorbital nerve mainly supplies nasal vestibule clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless ulcerative lesion with everted edges involving nasal vestibule is most suggestive of:",o:["Furunculosis","Rhinoscleroma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Vestibular papilloma"],a:2,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits painless ulcerative lesion with everted edges within nasal vestibule; characteristic malignant epithelial tumor presentation. Crusting and bleeding occur clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant squamous cells infiltrate local tissues and may metastasize regionally symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) presents painful boil; rhinoscleroma (option B) causes granulomatous fibrosis; vestibular papilloma (option D) remains benign. Therefore ulcerative vestibular lesions suggest squamous carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The olfactory mucosa is primarily supplied by fibers of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Olfactory nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"Olfactory nerve supply fits smell perception within olfactory mucosa; characteristic sensory receptor pathway of superior nasal cavity. Anosmia develops clinically after receptor damage.<br><br>Standard physiology: bipolar olfactory receptor neurons transmit impulses through cribriform plate toward olfactory bulb symptomatically.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) mediates taste partly; trigeminal nerve (option B) supplies general sensation; hypoglossal nerve (option D) controls tongue movement. Therefore olfactory nerve mediates smell clinically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops unilateral watery rhinorrhea after head trauma. The confirmatory diagnosis most likely is:",o:["Vasomotor rhinitis","Rhinoscleroma","Allergic rhinitis","CSF rhinorrhea"],a:3,e:"CSF rhinorrhea fits unilateral watery discharge after head trauma; characteristic skull base fracture complication. Meningitis risk increases clinically significantly if untreated.<br><br>Standard pathology: fractures involving cribriform plate create communication between subarachnoid space and nasal cavity symptomatically.<br><br>Vasomotor rhinitis (option A) causes bilateral rhinorrhea; allergic rhinitis (option C) associates sneezing; rhinoscleroma (option B) causes granulomatous obstruction. Therefore post traumatic watery rhinorrhea suggests CSF leakage clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which nasal deformity commonly follows improperly reduced nasal fracture?",o:["Rhinophyma","Saddle nose","Deviated nose","Choanal atresia"],a:2,e:"Deviated nose fits common deformity following inadequately treated nasal fracture; characteristic malalignment during healing process. Persistent obstruction develops clinically frequently afterward.<br><br>Standard pathology: displaced septal and nasal skeletal structures unite asymmetrically producing cosmetic and functional impairment symptomatically.<br><br>Rhinophyma (option A) results from rosacea; saddle nose (option B) follows cartilage destruction; choanal atresia (option D) remains congenital. Therefore malunited fractures commonly produce deviated nose clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest organism causing furunculosis of nasal vestibule is:",o:["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis","Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],a:2,e:"Staphylococcus aureus fits commonest causative organism of vestibular furunculosis; characteristic infection of hair follicles within vestibular skin. Pain and swelling occur clinically anteriorly.<br><br>Standard pathology: trauma from nose picking permits bacterial invasion producing localized abscess formation symptomatically.<br><br>Streptococcus pneumoniae (option A) commonly causes sinusitis; Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis (option B) causes rhinoscleroma; Pseudomonas aeruginosa (option D) commonly affects external ear. Therefore staphylococcal infection predominates clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The upper one third of external nose is formed primarily by:",o:["Septal cartilage","Inferior turbinate","Alar cartilage","Nasal bones"],a:3,e:"Nasal bones form upper one third of external nose; characteristic rigid bony framework of nasal dorsum. Fractures occur clinically frequently after facial trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: paired nasal bones articulate superiorly with frontal bone and laterally with frontal process of maxilla symptomatically.<br><br>Septal cartilage (option A) forms central support inferiorly; alar cartilage (option C) shapes nostrils; inferior turbinate (option B) lies intranasally. Therefore upper external nose mainly consists of nasal bones clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Rhinoscleroma is classically associated with which histological finding?",o:["Reed Sternberg cells","Langhans giant cells","Mikulicz cells","Psammoma bodies"],a:2,e:"Mikulicz cells fit histopathology of rhinoscleroma; characteristic foamy macrophages containing causative organisms. Chronic granulomatous fibrosis develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Standard pathology: plasma cell infiltration and fibrosis accompany intracellular bacterial accumulation within respiratory mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Reed Sternberg cells (option A) indicate Hodgkin lymphoma; Langhans giant cells (option B) occur in tuberculosis; psammoma bodies (option D) appear in papillary tumors. Therefore Mikulicz cells characterize rhinoscleroma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A pearly translucent lesion with rolled edges over nasal dorsum is most suggestive of:",o:["Melanoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Fibroma","Hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma fits pearly translucent lesion with rolled margins over nasal dorsum; characteristic rodent ulcer appearance. Slow enlargement occurs clinically with local tissue invasion.<br><br>Standard pathology: ultraviolet induced malignant transformation of basal epidermal cells produces locally aggressive lesions symptomatically.<br><br>Melanoma (option A) usually appears pigmented; fibroma (option C) remains benign connective tumor; hemangioma (option D) arises from blood vessels. Therefore pearly rolled lesions indicate basal cell carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of epistaxis in children is:",o:["Woodruff plexus","Middle meatus","Little's area","Superior turbinate"],a:2,e:"Little area fits commonest site of childhood epistaxis; characteristic vascular plexus over anterior nasal septum. Minor trauma triggers clinically recurrent bleeding episodes.<br><br>Standard anatomy: Kiesselbach plexus contains fragile arterial anastomoses beneath thin mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Woodruff plexus (option A) produces posterior epistaxis in adults; middle meatus (option B) drains sinuses; superior turbinate (option D) contains olfactory mucosa. Therefore childhood epistaxis commonly arises from Little area clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent vestibular boils should be advised primarily to avoid:",o:["Cold drinks","Swimming","Loud noise","Nose picking"],a:3,e:"Nose picking avoidance fits prevention of recurrent vestibular boils; characteristic traumatic predisposition to follicular infection. Crusting and pain decrease clinically after behavioral modification.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated trauma permits staphylococcal invasion of vestibular skin and hair follicles symptomatically.<br><br>Cold drinks (option A) lack relation; loud noise (option C) affects hearing; swimming (option B) predisposes otitis externa mainly. Therefore avoiding nose picking reduces vestibular furunculosis clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The physiological role of nasal turbinates includes all except:",o:["Filtration of inspired air","Humidification of air","Voice production","Warming of air"],a:2,e:"Voice production exclusion fits physiology of nasal turbinates; characteristic nasal air conditioning structures. Rich vascular mucosa modifies clinically inspired airflow efficiently.<br><br>Standard physiology: turbinates increase mucosal surface area causing filtration, warming, and humidification of inhaled air symptomatically.<br><br>Filtration (option A), humidification (option B), and warming (option D) represent normal turbinate functions. Therefore turbinates do not primarily participate in voice production clinically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign epithelial tumor of nasal vestibule is:",o:["Papilloma","Melanoma","Chondrosarcoma","Osteoma"],a:0,e:"Papilloma fits common benign epithelial tumor of nasal vestibule; characteristic wart like exophytic lesion. Nasal irritation develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Standard pathology: benign squamous epithelial proliferation forms papillary projections over vestibular mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Melanoma (option B) remains malignant; chondrosarcoma (option C) arises from cartilage; osteoma (option D) develops from bone. Therefore papilloma commonly represents benign vestibular tumor clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition most classically produces a \"frog face\" deformity in advanced disease?",o:["Bilateral ethmoidal polyposis","Septal hematoma","Nasal vestibulitis","Rhinophyma"],a:0,e:"Bilateral ethmoidal polyposis fits frog face deformity in advanced disease; characteristic expansion of ethmoidal labyrinth and nasal bridge. Nasal obstruction becomes clinically severe.<br><br>Standard pathology: extensive polyps progressively widen nasal cavity and alter facial contours symptomatically.<br><br>Septal hematoma (option B) causes saddle nose risk; nasal vestibulitis (option C) remains localized infection; rhinophyma (option D) enlarges nasal tip only. Therefore advanced polyposis may produce frog face deformity clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with crusting, granulomatous nasal lesions, and woody induration most likely has:",o:["Furunculosis","Vestibular papilloma","Rhinoscleroma","CSF rhinorrhea"],a:2,e:"Rhinoscleroma fits granulomatous crusting lesions with woody nasal induration; characteristic chronic Klebsiella infection. Progressive obstruction develops clinically gradually over years.<br><br>Standard pathology: granulomatous inflammation and fibrosis infiltrate respiratory mucosa producing firm thickened tissues symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) causes acute boils; vestibular papilloma (option B) forms benign wart like growths; CSF rhinorrhea (option D) produces watery discharge. Therefore woody granulomatous lesions suggest rhinoscleroma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important immediate management of septal hematoma is:",o:["Observation only","Broad spectrum antihistamines","Surgical drainage","Nasal massage"],a:2,e:"Surgical drainage fits immediate management of septal hematoma; characteristic emergency intervention preventing cartilage necrosis. Nasal obstruction improves clinically rapidly afterward.<br><br>Standard treatment: evacuation of collected blood restores septal perichondrial blood supply symptomatically.<br><br>Observation only (option A) risks saddle nose deformity; antihistamines (option B) lack therapeutic role; nasal massage (option D) worsens trauma. Therefore urgent surgical drainage remains essential clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A boxer presents with broadening of the nasal bridge after repeated trauma. The deformity is most likely due to:",o:["Chronic septal hematoma fibrosis","Ethmoidal polyposis","Vestibular papilloma","Nasal glioma"],a:0,e:"Chronic septal hematoma fibrosis fits broad nasal deformity after repeated trauma; characteristic cartilage damage with abnormal healing. Nasal obstruction develops clinically progressively afterward.<br><br>Standard pathology: repeated septal injury disrupts vascular supply causing fibrosis, collapse, and deformity symptomatically.<br><br>Ethmoidal polyposis (option B) widens nasal cavity; vestibular papilloma (option C) forms localized lesions; nasal glioma (option D) remains congenital. Therefore repeated septal trauma commonly causes deformity clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The artery considered the \"artery of epistaxis\" in severe posterior nasal bleeding is:",o:["Facial artery","Sphenopalatine artery","Ophthalmic artery","Superior labial artery"],a:1,e:"Sphenopalatine artery fits severe posterior epistaxis source; characteristic terminal branch of maxillary artery within nasal cavity. Posterior bleeding becomes clinically difficult to control.<br><br>Standard anatomy: arterial branches enter through sphenopalatine foramen supplying posterior septum and lateral nasal wall symptomatically.<br><br>Facial artery (option A) mainly contributes anteriorly; ophthalmic artery (option C) supplies superior regions; superior labial artery (option D) supplies anterior septum. Therefore posterior epistaxis commonly arises from sphenopalatine artery clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with unilateral foul smelling nasal discharge should be suspected primarily of having:",o:["Allergic rhinitis","Foreign body nose","Rhinoscleroma","CSF rhinorrhea"],a:1,e:"Foreign body nose fits unilateral foul smelling discharge in children; characteristic retained nasal object presentation. Crusting and bleeding occur clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: local mucosal irritation and secondary infection produce offensive unilateral secretions symptomatically.<br><br>Allergic rhinitis (option A) causes bilateral watery discharge; rhinoscleroma (option C) progresses chronically; CSF rhinorrhea (option D) produces clear watery fluid. Therefore unilateral foul discharge suggests nasal foreign body clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which structure forms the major support of nasal tip?",o:["Nasal bones","Septal cartilage","Lower lateral cartilage","Inferior turbinate"],a:2,e:"Lower lateral cartilage fits major structural support of nasal tip; characteristic alar cartilage contribution to nostril contour. Tip deformities occur clinically after cartilage trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: paired lower lateral cartilages shape the nasal apex and nostril margins symptomatically.<br><br>Nasal bones (option A) support upper dorsum; septal cartilage (option B) provides central support; inferior turbinate (option D) lies intranasally. Therefore nasal tip mainly depends upon lower lateral cartilage clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ulcerative lesion over ala nasi develops local tissue destruction but minimal metastasis. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma","Chondroma","Melanoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Basal cell carcinoma fits ulcerative lesion causing local destruction with rare metastasis; characteristic rodent ulcer behavior. Slow progression occurs clinically over years.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant basal epidermal cells invade adjacent tissues while distant spread remains uncommon symptomatically.<br><br>Squamous cell carcinoma (option A) metastasizes earlier; melanoma (option C) behaves aggressively; chondroma (option B) remains benign. Therefore destructive minimally metastatic lesions suggest basal cell carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important reason neonates with bilateral choanal atresia become cyanotic is that infants are:",o:["Obligate nasal breathers","Mouth breathers normally","Unable to swallow","Unable to cry"],a:0,e:"Obligate nasal breathing fits neonatal cyanosis in bilateral choanal atresia; characteristic infant airway physiology. Respiratory distress improves clinically temporarily during crying episodes.<br><br>Standard physiology: newborns depend predominantly upon nasal airflow during feeding and rest symptomatically.<br><br>Mouth breathing normally (option B) becomes inadequate in neonates; inability to swallow (option C) lacks relation; inability to cry (option D) remains incorrect. Therefore choanal atresia causes cyanosis because infants breathe nasally clinically.<br><br><em>(BRS Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful erythematous swelling at the nasal vestibule should not be squeezed because of risk of:",o:["Glaucoma","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Conductive deafness","Facial fracture"],a:1,e:"Cavernous sinus thrombosis fits feared complication of squeezing vestibular furuncles; characteristic retrograde venous infection spread. Intracranial sepsis develops clinically dangerously.<br><br>Standard anatomy: valveless facial and ophthalmic veins communicate directly with cavernous sinus symptomatically.<br><br>Glaucoma (option A) affects intraocular pressure; conductive deafness (option C) involves middle ear; facial fracture (option D) follows trauma. Therefore manipulation of vestibular boils risks cavernous sinus thrombosis clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest benign tumor arising from sebaceous glands of nose in elderly alcoholics is:",o:["Papilloma","Fibroma","Rhinophyma","Hemangioma"],a:2,e:"Rhinophyma fits sebaceous gland hypertrophy over nose in elderly individuals; characteristic bulbous nasal enlargement. Cosmetic deformity develops clinically progressively.<br><br>Standard pathology: chronic rosacea produces fibrosis, vascular congestion, and sebaceous hyperplasia symptomatically.<br><br>Papilloma (option A) forms epithelial growths; fibroma (option B) arises from connective tissue; hemangioma (option D) develops from blood vessels. Therefore rhinophyma represents sebaceous hypertrophy clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which deformity is most commonly associated with congenital syphilis?",o:["Crooked nose","Hump nose","Saddle nose","Rhinophyma"],a:2,e:"Saddle nose fits congenital syphilis associated deformity; characteristic collapse of nasal dorsum from septal destruction. Cosmetic deformity becomes clinically obvious early.<br><br>Standard pathology: syphilitic inflammation destroys septal cartilage reducing structural nasal support symptomatically.<br><br>Crooked nose (option A) follows trauma; hump nose (option B) represents dorsal prominence; rhinophyma (option D) occurs in rosacea. Therefore congenital syphilis classically causes saddle nose clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent epistaxis and telangiectasias over face most likely has:",o:["Rhinoscleroma","Wegener granulomatosis","Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia","Vestibular papilloma"],a:2,e:"Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia fits recurrent epistaxis with facial telangiectasias; characteristic vascular dysplasia disorder. Bleeding episodes occur clinically repeatedly.<br><br>Standard pathology: fragile dilated vascular channels rupture easily causing mucosal hemorrhage symptomatically.<br><br>Rhinoscleroma (option A) causes granulomatous fibrosis; Wegener granulomatosis (option B) produces vasculitis; vestibular papilloma (option D) forms benign growths. Therefore recurrent vascular epistaxis suggests hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for the USMLE Step 1)</em>"},
  {q:"The roof of nasal cavity is closely related superiorly to the:",o:["Pituitary gland","Anterior cranial fossa","Middle ear","Maxillary sinus"],a:1,e:"Anterior cranial fossa relation fits superior anatomy of nasal roof; characteristic separation by cribriform plate region. Trauma may produce clinically cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea.<br><br>Standard anatomy: olfactory fibers traverse cribriform plate between nasal cavity and intracranial compartment symptomatically.<br><br>Pituitary gland (option A) lies within sella; middle ear (option C) remains temporal; maxillary sinus (option D) lies laterally. Therefore nasal roof closely relates to anterior cranial fossa clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A unilateral ulcerative lesion over nasal vestibule with cervical lymphadenopathy most strongly suggests:",o:["Furunculosis","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Rhinophyma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits ulcerative vestibular lesion with cervical nodal involvement; characteristic metastatic epithelial malignancy. Bleeding and crusting occur clinically frequently.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant squamous cells invade lymphatics causing regional nodal spread symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) remains localized infection; basal cell carcinoma (option C) rarely metastasizes; rhinophyma (option D) is benign. Therefore nodal disease with ulceration suggests squamous carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The structure most commonly injured in septal hematoma is the:",o:["Nasal bone","Inferior turbinate","Septal cartilage","Frontal sinus"],a:2,e:"Septal cartilage involvement fits septal hematoma injury; characteristic avascular cartilage dependent upon perichondrial nutrition. Necrosis develops clinically if untreated.<br><br>Standard pathology: blood accumulation separates cartilage from perichondrium causing ischemic compromise symptomatically.<br><br>Nasal bone (option A) fractures separately; inferior turbinate (option B) lies laterally; frontal sinus (option D) remains superior. Therefore septal hematoma threatens septal cartilage viability clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition classically produces offensive crusts with roomy nasal cavity?",o:["Furunculosis","Septal hematoma","Atrophic rhinitis","Vestibular papilloma"],a:2,e:"Atrophic rhinitis fits offensive crusting with widened nasal cavity; characteristic mucosal atrophy disorder. Fetor becomes clinically noticeable to surrounding individuals.<br><br>Standard pathology: turbinate atrophy and mucosal degeneration produce crust accumulation and secondary infection symptomatically.<br><br>Furunculosis (option A) causes painful boils; septal hematoma (option B) follows trauma; vestibular papilloma (option D) forms localized growths. Therefore roomy crusted cavities suggest atrophic rhinitis clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which artery is a branch of ophthalmic artery contributing to Little's area?",o:["Sphenopalatine artery","Superior labial artery","Greater palatine artery","Anterior ethmoidal artery"],a:3,e:"Anterior ethmoidal artery fits ophthalmic arterial contribution to Little area; characteristic septal vascular anastomosis. Anterior epistaxis develops clinically commonly from fragile mucosal vessels.<br><br>Standard anatomy: anterior ethmoidal branches descend through cribriform region supplying superior septum symptomatically.<br><br>Sphenopalatine artery (option A) arises from maxillary artery; superior labial artery (option B) branches facial artery; greater palatine artery (option C) also arises maxillary artery. Therefore anterior ethmoidal artery derives from ophthalmic circulation clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive nasal obstruction and woody nasal swelling from endemic region most likely has:",o:["Vestibular furunculosis","Rhinoscleroma","CSF rhinorrhea","Nasal fracture"],a:1,e:"Rhinoscleroma fits progressive woody nasal swelling with obstruction in endemic regions; characteristic chronic granulomatous infection. Fibrosis develops clinically slowly over years.<br><br>Standard pathology: Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis infection stimulates granulomatous inflammation and scarring within respiratory mucosa symptomatically.<br><br>Vestibular furunculosis (option A) presents acutely painful lesions; CSF rhinorrhea (option C) causes watery discharge; nasal fracture (option D) follows trauma. Therefore woody endemic nasal disease suggests rhinoscleroma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The lower two thirds of external nose are formed predominantly by:",o:["Bone","Fibrous tissue","Cartilage","Muscle"],a:2,e:"Cartilage formation fits lower two thirds of external nose; characteristic flexible support framework of nasal tip and alae. Deformities develop clinically after cartilage trauma.<br><br>Standard anatomy: septal, upper lateral, and lower lateral cartilages form inferior nasal framework symptomatically.<br><br>Bone (option A) predominates upper third only; fibrous tissue (option B) provides support minimally; muscle (option D) controls nostril movement. Therefore lower external nose mainly consists of cartilage clinically.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful vestibular swelling with central pustule most likely represents infection of:",o:["Sebaceous gland only","Ethmoidal sinus","Hair follicle","Lacrimal sac"],a:2,e:"Hair follicle infection fits painful vestibular swelling with central pustule; characteristic furunculosis lesion. Tenderness develops clinically near vibrissae bearing areas.<br><br>Standard pathology: staphylococcal infection of vestibular hair follicles produces localized abscess formation symptomatically.<br><br>Sebaceous gland only (option A) underestimates follicular origin; ethmoidal sinus (option B) lies internally; lacrimal sac (option D) drains tears. Therefore vestibular boils arise from infected hair follicles clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant tumor of nasal vestibule is:",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Osteoma","Fibroma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits commonest malignant tumor of nasal vestibule; characteristic ulcerative epithelial malignancy. Cervical nodal spread develops clinically more frequently than basal carcinoma.<br><br>Standard pathology: malignant squamous epithelium invades local tissues aggressively with metastatic potential symptomatically.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (option A) commonly affects skin externally; osteoma (option C) remains benign bone tumor; fibroma (option D) is benign connective tissue lesion. Therefore vestibular malignancy commonly represents squamous carcinoma clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which nasal condition is most likely to require urgent drainage rather than antibiotic therapy alone?",o:["Vestibular furunculosis","Allergic rhinitis","Septal hematoma","Atrophic rhinitis"],a:2,e:"Septal hematoma fits nasal condition requiring urgent drainage; characteristic risk of cartilage necrosis with delayed treatment. Nasal obstruction appears clinically rapidly after trauma.<br><br>Standard pathology: accumulated blood separates septal cartilage from nourishing perichondrium causing ischemic injury symptomatically.<br><br>Vestibular furunculosis (option A) primarily requires antibiotics; allergic rhinitis (option B) responds medically; atrophic rhinitis (option D) causes crusting. Therefore septal hematoma mandates immediate drainage clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
];